result.execSummary:
Aaron Killebrew was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Aaron Killebrew was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Aaron Killebrew

records.addlTxt: Defendant picked up by Illinois Dept of Corrections.08/26/22

2:00 PM Defendant Aaron Killebrew in court, in custody. District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Abigail Kincheloe.  Attorney Public Defender Intern, Erik Schlueter appears as friend of the court. 
Court informs defendant of extradition rights.  Court advises of right to an attorney. Defendant was not evaluated by the public defender's office.  Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint. Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties.  Defendant waives his right to extradition.  State requests bond not be set for the defendant and that he be held without bail.  Defense requests bail be set.  Court withholds bail at this time.  Defendant is remanded to the Waukesha County Sheriff's department for extradition to the State of Illinois.  State of Illinois is to be notified that the defendant is available for pick up.
Hearing scheduled for September 15, 2022 at 08:30 am.
